This script produces the descriptive analysis of the main dataset (cand_skin_results).

Missing image data

Main takeaways:

  • A total of 21 candidates (1.69%) are missing data from both, their INE profile and SaberVotar profile. These candidates are from the MC party and the PAN-PRI-PRD coalition. They are part of the congress race and senate race. They belong to the states: Mexico, Jalisco, Guanajuato, San Luis Potosi, Coahuila, Oaxaca, Mexico City, Chiapas, Quintana Roo, and Guerrero.
  • A total of 165 candidates (13.29%) are missing data from their INE profile.
  • A total of 53 candidates (4.27%) are missing data from their SaberVotar profile.
  • The SaberVotar data has a lower proportion of missing data. Therefore, a possible solution is to impute skin color data from the SaberVotar profile to the INE profile. The final skin color measure could be the average of both measures.

Correlations with outcome variable:

  • The existance of an INE profile picture is weakly and positively correlated with electoral success (r=0.14).
  • The existance of a SaberVotar profile picture is weakly and positively correlated with electoral success (r=0.05).
  • The existance of a social media profile (a rough proxy for presence in public media environment) is weakly and positively correlated with electoral success (r=0.12).

Skin tone distribution

Main takeaways:

  • The skin tone classification algorithm was not able to measure the skin tone of 78 candidates. This number represents 7.46% of the candidates with image data and 6.28% of the total candidates in the dataset. This issue may be resolved by adjusting the algorithmâs facial detection parameters.
  • The overall skin tone distribution is slightly left-skewed, indicating that most candidates have a medium-dark skin tone. The mean skin tone is 7.1 and the standard deviation is 1.72. The skin tone distribution is shown in the following figure.
